Credit Card Debt Prediction¶

Project Overview¶

This notebook demonstrates a predictive model for credit card debt (Balance) using customer attributes from credit.csv. We perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), build a linear regression model, evaluate model diagnostics, and suggest improvements.

1. Problem Definition¶

We aim to predict Balance (average credit card debt) for each customer based on various attributes like income, credit limit, credit rating, and demographic data.

Plot histogram and QQ plot to check normality of residuals¶

In [13]:
sns.histplot(residuals, kde=True)
plt.title("Histogram of Residuals")
plt.show()

sm.qqplot(residuals, line="45")
plt.title("QQ Plot of Residuals")
plt.show()

Ideally, residuals should follow a normal (bell-shaped) distribution, centered around zero. But the histogram shows skewness, it might imply that the model is systematically over- or under-predicting for certain values, possibly indicating the need for data transformation or more complex models.

The QQ plot compares the quantiles of the residuals to the quantiles of a theoretical normal distribution. Ideally, the points should fall along a 45-degree line, meaning the residuals closely follow a normal distribution. But our graph indicates that your residuals do not follow a normal distribution, deviating significantly from the 45-degree line expected in a normal QQ plot.

Perform Shapiro-Wilk test for normality¶

In [14]:
shapiro_test = shapiro(residuals)
print("Shapiro-Wilk Test p-value:", shapiro_test.pvalue)

Shapiro-Wilk Test p-value: 4.680319326761673e-08

The Shapiro-Wilk Test results indicate that the residuals from your regression model are not normally distributed

In [16]:
# Calculate Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) to check for multicollinearity
vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["feature"] = X.columns
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_train_scaled, i) for i in range(X_train_scaled.shape[1])]
print("Variance Inflation Factors (VIF):")
print(vif_data)

Severe Multicollinearity:

Limit (VIF = 247.41) and Rating (VIF = 250.95): These two features exhibit severe multicollinearity with extremely high VIF values. Their inclusion in the model may distort the estimated coefficients and inflate standard errors, making them unreliable for inference. We must consider removing one or both of these variables, or combining them if they capture similar information.

In [17]:
# Make predictions on the test set
X_test_sm = sm.add_constant(X_test_scaled)
y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_sm)

# Calculate RMSE and R-squared
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

print("Test RMSE:", rmse)
print("Test R-squared:", r2)

Test RMSE: 89.3020517655732
Test R-squared: 0.9522674050276406

A Test RMSE of 89.30 and a Test R-squared of 0.95 indicate strong model performance, suggesting that the model explains about 95% of the variance in the credit card debt prediction.
